              <table id="improv" class="display" cellspacing="1" width="100%">
                      <thead>
                          <tr>
                              <th>Name</th>
                              <th>Type</th>
                              <th>Difficulty</th>
                              <th>Description</th>
                              <th>Notes/Related Games</th>
                              <th>Source</th>
                          </tr>
                      </thead>

                      <tbody>
                                <td><a href="#">Yes, and</a></td>
                              <td>verbal, warm-up</td>
                              <td>easy</td>
                              <td>The first player makes a declarative statement, and the following player agrees with and then adds to the statement. The idea is to heighten whatever information was given.</td>

                              <td>This is the basic dynamic of most improv games and scenes, in the same way that the genga is the move in capoiera that other moves are derived from.</td>
                              <td>Improv Olympic</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                              <td>Add-on</td>
                              <td>physical</td>
                              <td>easy</td>
                              <td>The first player, usually stepping into the middle of a circle or out of a line, does some kind of a simple physical gesture. Depending on the age group, location, and type of class these could range from the acrobatic to minimal. The next player repaets the initial gesture or action and then adds their own.</td>
                              <td>You could combine this with one-word story for a kind of performance slam poetry.</td>
                              <td>unknown</td>
                          </tr>
